  <static seed="1058" source="PCC-ORCCA-ed3/BasicAlgebra/QuadraticApplications/FlyingObjectApp30.pg">
    <statement><p>A remote control aircraft will perform a stunt by flying toward the ground and then up. Its height, in feet, can be modeled by the equation <m>h={1.6t^{2}-12.8t+23.6}</m>, where <m>t</m> is in seconds. The plane <ul form="popup" name="AnSwEr0001"><li>
<p>?</p>
</li><li>
<p>will</p>
</li><li>
<p>will not</p>
</li></ul> hit the ground during this stunt.</p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\text{will}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To determine whether the plane will hit the ground, we substitute <m>h(t)=0</m> into <m>h(t)={1.6t^{2}-12.8t+23.6}</m>, and solve the equation by the Quadratic Formula:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{
        \begin{aligned}
            t \amp  = \frac{-b\pm\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}\\
              \amp  = \frac{-({-12.8})\pm\sqrt{({-12.8})^2-4(1.6)({23.6})}}{2(1.6)}\\
                   \amp  = \frac{{12.8}\pm\sqrt{{163.84}-{151.04}}}{3.2}\\
                   \amp  = \frac{{12.8}\pm\sqrt{{12.8}}}{3.2}\\
                  \amp \approx \frac{12.8\pm 3.58}{3.2} \\\amp \approx \frac{12.8+3.58}{3.2}\text{ or }\frac{12.8-3.58}{3.2} \\\amp \approx 5.12\text{ or }2.88
        \end{aligned}
     }</m></p>
<p>The plane would hit the ground approximately `2.88` seconds into the stunt.</p>
</solution>
